<section xml:id="section-assignment5">
  <title>Assignment 5</title>
  <p><ol>
    <li>
      <p>
        Prove that the following limits do not exist. (Assumed the
        functions are defined on maximum possible domains). (10)
        <ol>
          <li> 
            <me>
              \lim_{(x,y) \rightarrow (0,0)}  \frac{x^2 + xy -
              y^2}{|xy|} 
            </me>
          </li>
          <li> 
            <me>
              \lim_{(x,y) \rightarrow (3,3)} \frac{y-3}{x-3}
            </me>
          </li>
        </ol>
      </p>
    </li>
    <li>
      <p>
        Consider this function. (6)
        <me>
          f(x,y) = \frac{x^3 + y^3}{x+y} 
        </me>
        This function is not defined on the line <m>x = -y</m>. What
        values would you define on that line to make the function
        continuous?
      </p>
    </li>
    <li>
      <p>
        Let <m>a</m> and <m>b</m> be real numbers. Consider this
        function. (4)
        <me>
          f(x,y) = \frac{x-a}{y-b}
        </me>
        For what values of <m>a</m> and <m>b</m> does this limit
        exist? 
      </p>
    </li>
    <li>
      <p>
        Calculate all the partial derivatives of the following
        functions. (12)
        <ol>
          <li>
            <m>f(x,y,z) = z \sin (x + y) + x \cos (y + z)</m>
          </li>
          <li>
            <m>f(x,y,z) = x^2yz + y^z + z^2 (x^2 - y^2)</m>
          </li>
          <li>
            <m>f(x,y,z) = \frac{e^{xy} - e^{yz}}{y^2}</m>
          </li>
        </ol>
      </p>
    </li>
    <li>
      <p>
        Draw a contour graph for the function <m>f(x,y) =
        \frac{1}{(x^2 + 1)(y^2 + 1)}</m>. Identify some points where
        both of the partial derivatives vanish. Describe the level
        curves close to these points. (8)
      </p>
    </li>
    <li>
      <p>
        Draw a contour graph for the function <m>f(x,y) =
        \frac{\sin x}{y^2 + 1}</m>. Identify some points where
        both of the partial derivatives vanish. Describe the level
        curves close to these points. (8)
      </p>
    </li>
    <li>
      <p>
        Let <m>f(x,y)</m> be a differentiable function. Prove that if
        <m>\frac{\del f}{\del x}</m> and <m>\frac{\del f}{\del y}</m>
        are constant, then the graph of <m>f</m> must be a plane in
        <m>\RR^3</m>.
      </p>
    </li>
    <li>
      <p>
        Let <m>f(x,y)</m> be a differentiable function where 
        <m>\frac{\del f}{\del x} = g(y)</m> and <m>\frac{\del f}{\del
        y} = h(x)</m> for some single variable functions <m>g</m> and
        <m>h</m>. What does this say about the function <m>f</m>? (6) 
      </p>
    </li>
  </ol></p>
</section>
